##Two U.S. lawmakers have declared self-imposed quarantine

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Nan Boyi, _ the_paper _ reporter

On March 8, two members of the Republican Party announced a 14-day self-imposed quarantine after attending a meeting of conservative political action (CPAC) in Maryland. On March 7, the American conservative coalition (Acu) announced that a participant at the conservative political action conference the previous week had been diagnosed with new pneumonia.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ted Cruz

According to a report by the CNN on March 8, Texas Senator and Republican Ted Cruz and Arizona Representative and Republican Paul Gossart said respectively that, they will be quarantined for 14 days and proceed with caution. So far, the two men have not developed any symptoms of the new coronavirus infection.

Cruz said he would stay in Texas for 14 days. He said he had had a "simple conversation and handshake" with a confirmed patient, but it lasted less than a minute and the health authorities considered the risk of infection low.

Paul Gossart said in a statement late on the 8th that he had spent a lot of time with the person diagnosed, "shaking hands several times. ". He announced that he would spend 14 days at his home in Arizona and that his office would be closed for a week.

The conservative political action conference was held in Maryland from February 26 to 29. President Donald Trump, vice president Michel Pensée and other senior officials attended the meeting.

On March 7, the conservative coalition of America released a statement saying that a participant had been diagnosed with new pneumonia, but that the participant had no contact with Donald Trump or Michel Pensée, nor had he attended the event that day at the main venue. Donald Trump also said he was not concerned after hearing the news.
